					</math.display>
				</answer>
				
				<solution>
					<computation>
						<left>B^T\cdot A^T</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
							-3 & -8 & 0 \\
							 1 & -2 & 1 \\
							 -9 & 4 & 3
							\end{array}\right]\ \cdot\ 
							\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
							1 & 3 & -5 \\
							1 & -4 & 0 \\
							3 & 2 & -1
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							B^T \cdot A^T\ =\ 
							\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
							-11 & 23 & 15 \\
							2 & 13 & -6 \\
							4 & -37 & 42
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
					</computation>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para>How is the matrix <latex>AB</latex> related to the matrix <latex>B^T\cdot A^T</latex>?</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para>Computing the two matrices shows that</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>B^T \cdot A^T\ =\ (AB)^T</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Given: the matrices <latex>A</latex> and <latex>B</latex> below, perform the specified operations, provided they are defined. If they are not defined, say why not.</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
					A\ =\ 
					\left[\begin{array}{rr}
					-4 & 3 \\
					3 & -4 \\
					1 & 0 \\
					2 & 2
					\end{array}\right] \qquad\quad
					\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
					2 & 1 & -5  & -3 \\
					-1 & -2 & -3 & 0 \\
					0 & 4 & -1 & 1 \\
					3 & -1 & 2 & -2
					\end{array}\right]
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
		</problem>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>A + B</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>Addition of matrices is only defined for matrices of equal size. Now, <latex>A</latex> has size <latex>(4,2)</latex>, while <latex>B</latex> has size <latex>(4,4)</latex>. Therefore the matrix sum <latex>A + B</latex> is not defined in this case.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>B - A</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>We need to consider the expression</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>B\ +\ (-1)\cdot A</latex>
					</math.display>
					
					<para>Addition of matrices is only defined for matrices of equal size. Now, <latex>B</latex> has size <latex>(4,4)</latex>, while <latex>(-1)\cdot </latex> has the same size as <latex>A</latex>, namely <latex>(4,2)</latex>. Therefore the matrix sum <latex>B - A</latex> is not defined in this case.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para>AB</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>For <latex>AB</latex> to be defined, the number of columns of <latex>A</latex> must equal the number of rows of <latex>B</latex>. Now the number of columns of <latex>A</latex> is <latex>2</latex>, while the number of rows of <latex>B</latex> is <latex>4</latex>. Therefore the matrix product <latex>AB</latex> is not defined in this case.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para>BA</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para>The matrix product <latex>BA</latex> is defined as the number of columns of <latex>B</latex> is equal to the number of rows of <latex>A</latex>, namely <latex>4</latex>. We find</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
							B\cdot A\ =\ 
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-16 & -4 \\
							-5 & 5 \\
							13 & -14 \\
							17 & 9
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>BA - A</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>We know from the previous part that <latex>BA</latex> has size <latex>(4,2)</latex>, which agrees with the size of <latex>A</latex>. Therefore the specified matrix operation <latex>BA + A</latex> is defined, and the result is</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>BA + A</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							2 & 1 & -5  & -3 \\
							-1 & -2 & -3 & 0 \\
							0 & 4 & -1 & 1 \\
							3 & -1 & 2 & -2
							\end{array}\right] \cdot 
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-4 & 3 \\
							3 & -4 \\
							1 & 0 \\
							2 & 2
							\end{array}\right]\ +\ 
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-4 & 3 \\
							3 & -4 \\
							1 & 0 \\
							2 & 2
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-16 & -4 \\
							-5 & 5 \\
							13 & -14 \\
							17 & 9
							\end{array}\right]\ +\
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-4 & 3 \\
							3 & -4 \\
							1 & 0 \\
							2 & 2
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-20 & -1 \\
							-2 & 1 \\
							14 & -14 \\
							-15 & 11
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
					</computation>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>3A</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>The scalar product <latex>t\cdot A</latex> of a matrix <latex>A</latex> by a number <latex>t</latex> is always defined. In the case at hand we get</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
							3\cdot A\ =\ 
							\left[\begin{array}{rr}
							-12 & 9 \\
							9 & -12 \\
							3 & 0 \\
							6 & 6
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>(-2)\cdot B</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>The scalar product <latex>t\cdot B</latex> of a matrix <latex>B</latex> by a number <latex>t</latex> is always defined. In the case at hand we get</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
							(-2)\cdot B\ =\ 
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							-4 & -2 & 10 & 6 \\
							2 & 4 & 6 & 0 \\
							0 & -8 & 2 & -2 \\
							-6 & 2 & -4 & 4
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>A^T</latex> and <latex>B^T</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>The transpose of a matrix is always defined. In the two cases at hand, we get</para>
					<computation>
						<left>A^T</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							-4 & 3 & 1 & 2 \\
							3 & -4 & 0 & 2
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
						<left>B^T</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							2 & -1 & 0 & 3 \\
							1 & -2 & 4 & -1 \\
							-5 & -3 & -1 & 2 \\
							-3 & 0 & 1 & -2
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
					</computation>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>A^T B^T</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution>
					<para>The number of columns of <latex>A^T</latex> is <latex>4</latex>, and this equals the number of rows of <latex>B^T</latex>. Therefore the matrix product <latex>A^T B^T</latex> is defined. We obtain</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>A^T\cdot B^T</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							-4 & 3 & 1 & 2 \\
							3 & -4 & 0 & 2
							\end{array}\right] \cdot 
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							2 & -1 & 0 & 3 \\
							1 & -2 & 4 & -1 \\
							-5 & 03 & -1 & 2 \\
							-3 & 0 & 1 & -2
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
							\left[\begin{array}{rrrr}
							-16 & -5 & 13 & -17 \\
							-4 & 5 & -14 & 9
							\end{array}\right]
							]]>
						</right>
					</computation>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem><para><latex>B^T A^T</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<solution.hint>
					<para>Check if the number of columns of <latex>B^T</latex> equals the number of rows of <latex>A^T</latex>.</para>
				</solution.hint>
				<solution>
					<para><latex>B^T</latex> has <latex>4</latex> columns, while <latex>A^T</latex> has <latex>2</latex> rows. For <latex>B^TA^T</latex> to be defined these two numbers would have to be equal. So the given product is not defined.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
